<lb/><foreign xml:lang="grc">θλασμένῳ</foreign>, confirmatur et a Galeno, qui <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἔνθλασμά τι μι-</foreign><lb break="no"/><foreign xml:lang="grc">κρὸν</foreign> in fructu adesse asserit<ref target="#fn64">64</ref>, quod sine dubio ad emar<lb break="no"/>ginatam apice siliculam Thlaspeos reducendum. Non de<lb break="no"/>sunt tamen, qui peregrinam statuant originem, quam Ros<lb break="no"/>sius ex aegyptiaco <foreign xml:lang="grc">λάψι</foreign> eruere conatur<ref target="#fn65">65</ref>, licet adsit ap<lb break="no"/>pellatio alia aegyptiaca <foreign xml:lang="grc">σονιτέμψος</foreign>, de qua nihil habet,
<lb/>quod lucem afferat. Descriptio Dioscoridis optime qua<lb break="no"/>drat in <hi rend="italic">Thlaspi Bursam</hi>. Sed Galeni thlaspeos duo
<lb/>genera e Cappadocia obscura sunt, sicut et Cratevae per<lb break="no"/>sicum sinapi, quod infra (c. 204.) ad Capparin refertur.
